body:
@micophilip, thanks for reporting the issue.

First, please try default session option (NOT set intra_op_num_threads) or set intra_op_num_threads to number of cores. That's the best setting if you use onnxruntime_gpu package.

If that could not solve the issue. Please try [benchmark](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/run_benchmark.sh) on those two machines to see whether it could reproduce the issue.

You can change the settings in the benchmark script like the following (You might update batch size and sequence length according to your data) since your model has no attention mask input and inference is on CPU :
```
run_gpu_fp32=false
run_gpu_fp16=false
run_cpu_fp32=true
run_cpu_int8=false
batch_sizes="1"
sequence_lengths="8 128"
input_counts=2
models_to_test="bert-base-cased"
```

@micophilip, 

onnxruntime package is built with OpenMP and onnxruntime_gpu does not. For CPU inference, onnxruntime package usually is better.

@tianleiwu this is the output from result.csv after running the `run_benchmark.sh`, not sure how to interpret this result, but I did notice that the `torchscript` engine test came back on the console much quicker than the `onnxruntime`

|model_name|inputs|engine|version|device|precision|optimizer|io_binding|b1_s8|b1_s128|b1_s512|
|--|--|--|--|--|--|--|--|--|--|--|
|bert-base-cased|1|torchscript|1.5.1|cpu|fp32|||11.13|37.55|109.34|
|bert-base-cased|1|torchscript|1.5.1|cpu|fp32|||10.61|41.44|149.86|
|bert-base-cased|2|onnxruntime|1.4.0|cpu|fp32|True|True|11.28|25.84|90.80|
|bert-base-cased|2|onnxruntime|1.4.0|cpu|fp32|True|False|8.84|28.76|89.44|

@micophilip, the table is average latency for different batch size (b) and sequence length (s). It seems that OnnxRuntime is faster in that test. For example batch_size=1 and sequence length 128, latency is 28.76ms for OnnxRuntime without IO Binding, and 37.55ms for PyTorch. That is about 23% speed up.

@tianleiwu I wonder how these results are calculated ðŸ¤” I ran the script again twice, once with only `run_ort=true` and once with only `run_torchscript=true`. In each run, I echoed the timestamp in the `run_benchmark.sh` before the inference and after it. The onnx run took 262 seconds from start to finish of inference, the torchscript took 153 seconds.

Here's the full output with echoed timestamps for the ONNX run
[onnx.log](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/5156975/onnx.log)

Here's the full output with echoed timestamps for the pytorch run
[pytorch.log](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/5156977/pytorch.log)

@micophilip, In the benchmark, a random input is generated, and inference latency is measured, and averaged over 1000 times.

ONNX run has more tests than PyTorch (6 vs 3). It is because we tested two settings (with/without IO Binding) in ONNX run.

For example, for input shape [1, 8], ONNX run has two tests (a blank line is added to see it clearly):
```
Tue Sep 1 10:27:14 EDT 2020
Run onnxruntime on bert-base-cased with input shape [1, 8]
{'engine': 'onnxruntime', 'version': '1.4.0', 'device': 'cpu', 'optimizer': True, 'precision': <Precision.FLOAT32: 'fp32'>, 'io_binding': False, 'model_name': 'bert-base-cased', 'inputs': 2, 'batch_size': 1, 'sequence_length': 8, 'datetime': '2020-09-01 10:27:36.371107', 'test_times': 1000, 'latency_variance': '0.00', 'latency_90_percentile': '7.69', 'latency_95_percentile': '7.99', 'latency_99_percentile': '8.55', 'average_latency_ms': '7.50', 'QPS': '133.30'}

Run onnxruntime with io binding on bert-base-cased with input shape [1, 8]
{'engine': 'onnxruntime', 'version': '1.4.0', 'device': 'cpu', 'optimizer': True, 'precision': <Precision.FLOAT32: 'fp32'>, 'io_binding': True, 'model_name': 'bert-base-cased', 'inputs': 2, 'batch_size': 1, 'sequence_length': 8, 'datetime': '2020-09-01 10:27:36.371107', 'test_times': 1000, 'latency_variance': '0.00', 'latency_90_percentile': '7.68', 'latency_95_percentile': '8.42', 'latency_99_percentile': '10.85', 'average_latency_ms': '7.56', 'QPS': '132.28'}
```
PyTorch has only one:
```
Tue Sep 1 10:36:56 EDT 2020
Run PyTorch on bert-base-cased with input shape [1, 8]
{'engine': 'torchscript', 'version': '1.5.1', 'device': 'cpu', 'optimizer': '', 'precision': <Precision.FLOAT32: 'fp32'>, 'io_binding': '', 'model_name': 'bert-base-cased', 'inputs': 1, 'batch_size': 1, 'sequence_length': 8, 'datetime': '2020-09-01 10:37:14.835681', 'test_times': 1000, 'latency_variance': '0.00', 'latency_90_percentile': '10.51', 'latency_95_percentile': '10.83', 
'latency_99_percentile': '11.02', 'average_latency_ms': '10.30', 'QPS': '97.09'}
```
So, if you divide 262 seconds by 2, it will yield 131 seconds. That will be smaller than 153 seconds.

I noticed the benchmark script does not actually fine-tune the BERT model and just runs the inference against the pre-trained model. That's one difference between that and my test case where I actually fine-tune `bert-base-uncased` and run inference on it.

Since none of the recommended options worked for me (such as unsetting `intra_op_num_threads`) and since I'm already using the default settings to `export` and to instantiate an inference session, there's no point of dragging this any longer so I'll just close the issue.

I do encourage the ONNX team however to add to their test suites this scenario of using a fine-tuned `bert-base-uncased` and running inference on it on Linux as it's been consistently slower than PyTorch on Linux CentOS for me no matter what dataset I use.
